post_text: Tonight, we shared our return-to-learning plan to the Board of Education. The plan's primary focus is student and educator safety. The plan includes Pre-K - 8th graders returning with a mix of in-building, and at-home learning. We will include multiple layers of health protections at the Pre-K 8 schools. A virtual option - the Euclid Virtual Learning Academy will be available to families who prefer online learning. Our high school will return with a virtual learning option, with opportunities for students to receive individualized support from our teachers. For more, click below.

Euclid Schools Reopening Plan Summary
text:
Tonight, we shared our return-to-learning plan to the Board of Education. The plan's primary focus is student and educator safety. The plan includes Pre-K - 8th graders returning with a mix of in-building, and at-home learning. We will include multiple layers of health protections at the Pre-K 8 schools. A virtual option - the Euclid Virtual Learning Academy will be available to families who prefer online learning. Our high school will return with a virtual learning option, with opportunities for students to receive individualized support from our teachers. For more, click below.

post_text:
Incoming 8th graders, not sure where to start with your summer reading? Let Euclid Public Library help you out! Parents and/or students can call ahead (216-261-5300) and request the book of their choice and they can have it ready for when you arrive, so long as the book is available. You can also reach them on their live chat line on the library‚Äôs homepage at euclidlibrary.org on the top left hand side of the page. Or, if you just stop in, they can pull the book when you get there if it‚Äôs available.

Also, if you need assistance with accessing or navigating Libby, Hoopla, or Overdrive, Ms. Temah and Mr. Ray host a weekly Zoom session (Level Up: Virtual Skills for the Virtual Classroom) every Wednesday from 3:00 to 4:00 pm to help guide and answer any questions. Use the link below:

https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZIqf-iprDouGdJVZHvq7hZO8j-1-OE8-7lz

post_text: Euclid High School will join high schools around the state and country in lighting up our stadium lights tonight in support of our senior class. The Ohio High School Athletic Association has asked schools across the state to turn their stadium lights on at 8:20 p.m. (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes to celebrate and honor the Class of 2020. Residents who want to support our seniors are asked to turn your porch lights on at 8:20 p.m.

post_text:
The Ohio House of Representatives extended the vote by mail deadline for the March 17 primary election to April 28.

post_text: There will be no in-person voting today per the order of the state health director. More information will be posted as it becomes available.
shared_text:
Governor Mike DeWine
March 17 at 2:13 AM ¬∑

During this time when we face an unprecedented public health crisis, to conduct an election tomorrow would force poll workers and voters to place themselves at an unacceptable health risk of contracting coronavirus. As such, Health Director Dr. Amy Acton will order the polls closed as a health emergency. While the polls will be closed tomorrow, Secretary of State Frank LaRose will seek a remedy through the courts to extend voting options so that every voter who wants to vote will be granted that opportunity.
text:
There will be no in-person voting today per the order of the state health director. More information will be posted as it becomes available.

Governor Mike DeWine
March 17 at 2:13 AM ¬∑

During this time when we face an unprecedented public health crisis, to conduct an election tomorrow would force poll workers and voters to place themselves at an unacceptable health risk of contracting coronavirus. As such, Health Director Dr. Amy Acton will order the polls closed as a health emergency. While the polls will be closed tomorrow, Secretary of State Frank LaRose will seek a remedy through the courts to extend voting options so that every voter who wants to vote will be granted that opportunity.

post_text: There have been rumors recently posted on Facebook claiming that the restrooms in the new secondary campus, currently under construction have been destroyed and that there is graffiti on the new building. We have found no signs of vandalism of any kind in the new construction. Our students and community have been very respectful during this construction process. We are proud of the work being completed in our district that will provide students with new state-of-the-art middle and high school buildings designed to improve their learning environment. The completed buidlings will be an asset to our community with opportunities for recreation and community events. If you have questions about the new campus, please send a message to Euclid City Schools through the Facebook page or email public relations and marketing coordinator Kurt Moore at kdmoore@euclidschools.org.

post_text: Media outlets are reporting that there will be a shortage of 400,000 welders by 2024. Euclid High School's award-winning welding career tech prep program, taught by instructor Ryan Eubank in partnership with Lincoln Electric, is preparing students to help fill this gap. The program now housed at Lincoln Electric is scheduled to move into a state-of-the-art lab at our new Euclid High School when it opens next year. Here's some information that we shared about the welding program in October. http://www.euclidschools.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6G2UA22&dasi=4GAUB #CareerTechOhio

post_text: Euclid City Schools will offer four opportunities for families and community members to learn more about our focus on student achievement, fiscal responsibility and credibility.

post_text:
Euclid City Schools' Student Services Department has moved to 22800 Fox Avenue. Student registration, transcripts, work permits and other student services will be located at the Memorial Building.

The public entrance is on the side of Memorial Building near Milton Avenue. Visitors will need to enter off Babbitt Road and use the public parking lot near the Euclid Skatepark. There will be no public entrance on Fox Avenue.

Euclid Schools continues to register students for every grade level. Student registration is open 8 a.m.-4:30 p.m. weekdays.

For more information, call 216-797-2931.
